## 2. Standing rule for all future campaign designs

Every future campaign design must be fully contained in one Markdown file and
must contain all of the following:

1. a minimum release floor, never a maximum campaign scope;
2. protected mathematical, evidentiary, repository, and compatibility
   invariants;
3. an active expansion queue populated from known source-backed opportunities;
4. a mandatory discovery pass for valuable adjacent capabilities not anticipated
   when the handoff was drafted;
5. a promotion protocol covering authority, exact domain, laws, implementation,
   hostile tests, deterministic certificates, verifier replay, and theorem or
   ensemble updates;
6. typed runtime refusals for capabilities not yet promoted, explicitly described
   as temporary evidence boundaries rather than research prohibitions;
7. local blockers that quarantine only dependent work, allowing independent
   derivations to continue;
8. an expansion ledger in which every identified capability is `PROMOTED`,
   `ACTIVE_PROOF`, `BLOCKED(<named obligation>)`, or
   `REFUTED(<proof/counterexample>)`;
9. acceptance gates that grow when a valid expansion is adopted instead of
   silently discarding the expansion to preserve the original checklist; and
10. a self-contained final report recording both the original floor and all
    promoted extensions.

An experiment may still be explicitly frozen when the user wants a controlled
comparison.  Such a freeze must be labelled as an experimental constraint, not
as a mathematical limitation on the wider programme.

